What is this analysis?

This notebook is for selecting a game and identifying its most comparable games using data from boardgamegeek.com. I use a dimension reduction method (PCA) to learn the main points of variation in data about games from boardgamegeek. This gives me a vector with every games value on each of the principal components. To find similar games, I compute the distance between all games using the first ten principal components to compute their similarity. I compute the Manhattan distance (the sum of the absolute differences between two vectors) between all games in order to find games that are similar - that have the shortest distance between them.

Games that have similar data, such as the same mechanics, complexity, and playtime, will have shorter distances to each other than games that are very different. A games neighbors are its fellow games that have the shortest distance between then based on the observe data. This document displays a games 25 nearest neighbors and illustrate some of the dimensions that make the games similar.

Most Similar Games to Robinson Crusoe: Adventures on the Cursed Island

The table below displays the most similar games to Robinson Crusoe: Adventures on the Cursed Island using data from boardgamegeek (BGG). The reported similarity score is the (squared) inverse of the Manhattan distance between two games.

Note: The analysis does not make use of a games number of ratings, average, or geek average, but instead looks only at a games categories, mechanics, playing time, player count, and complexity. The current approach for computing the distance weighs each component equally; I plan to explore a change to this in the future by using different measures of distance, as we would reasonably expect some components to be more important than others. I initially relied on Euclidean distance, but in tinkering with the results I have opted to go with the Manhattan distance for now.

Examining PCA Variable Loadings

What explains a games score on each principal component?

To gain a better understanding of these principal components, we can look at the loadings for the variables in the dataset. These are the the contributions of each variable to the ten components used in computing the distance between games. Large loadings (either positive or negative) for a variable indicate that there is a strong relationship between that variable and the component.

For instance, on the first principal component (PC1), time per player, average weight, and playing time have the highest positive loadings, while party game and max players have negative loadings. This indicates that this component seems to map to a games complexity - longer, more complex games will have high positive scores on this component while simpler, shorter, party games with lots of players will have low scores.
